.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/feature_catalog/06--mcp-surface/02-advisor-status.md:2:title: "advisor_status MCP Tool"
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/feature_catalog/06--mcp-surface/02-advisor-status.md:3:description: "Diagnostic-only native MCP tool that reports advisor freshness, generation, trust state, skillCount, lastScanAt and canonical lane weights without rebuilding stale state."
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/feature_catalog/06--mcp-surface/02-advisor-status.md:5:  - "advisor_status"
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/feature_catalog/06--mcp-surface/02-advisor-status.md:7:  - "advisor freshness status"
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/feature_catalog/06--mcp-surface/02-advisor-status.md:11:# advisor_status MCP Tool
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/feature_catalog/06--mcp-surface/02-advisor-status.md:17:Give operators and runtimes a single diagnostic read that summarizes whether advisor state is healthy enough to trust for routing.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/feature_catalog/06--mcp-surface/02-advisor-status.md:21:`handlers/advisor-status.ts` returns `freshness`, `generation`, `trustState` (with `state` and optional `reason`), `skillCount`, `lastScanAt` and `laneWeights` (the canonical 5-lane configuration). Freshness vocabulary is `live / stale / absent / unavailable`. The call is fail-open: even when the daemon is absent, status returns a well-formed envelope describing the shortfall.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/feature_catalog/06--mcp-surface/02-advisor-status.md:23:`readAdvisorStatus()` is strictly diagnostic. It reports stale, absent or unavailable advisor state and does not repair it. Operators should call `advisor_rebuild` when status reports stale state or when a forced rebuild is needed.
