.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:2:name: system-skill-advisor
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:3:description: Routes non-trivial requests to matching skills through standalone MCP metadata and stable advisor tool ids.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:4:allowed-tools: [Read, Write, Edit, Bash, Glob, Grep]
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:7:  - "skill advisor"
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:9:  - "advisor_recommend"
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:10:  - "advisor_status"
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:12:  - "route this request to a skill"
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:13:  - "system skill advisor"
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:17:  - advisor-mcp
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:23:  - "advisor_recommend native MCP routing"
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:24:  - "advisor_status freshness check"
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:26:  - "run the skill advisor hook"
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:29:<!-- Keywords: system-skill-advisor, skill-advisor, advisor_recommend, advisor_status, advisor_rebuild, advisor_validate, skill_graph_scan, skill_graph_query, skill_graph_status, skill_graph_validate, skill_graph_propagate_enhances, cross-skill-edges, gate-2-routing, standalone-mcp, legacy-tool-bridge, skill-graph -->
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:41:Use this skill when the work is about skill selection, Gate 2 routing, advisor MCP tools, prompt-time skill-advisor hooks, skill graph freshness or the standalone advisor package.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:47:- An operator asks about `advisor_recommend`, `advisor_status`, `advisor_rebuild`, `advisor_validate`, `skill_graph_scan`, `skill_graph_query`, `skill_graph_status`, `skill_graph_validate` or `skill_graph_propagate_enhances`.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:48:- A packet touches the skill graph, skill metadata, advisor scorer, advisor feature catalog or manual testing playbook.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:51:Do not use this skill as a replacement for the recommended target skill. For example, route code implementation to `sk-code`, documentation authoring to `sk-doc`, git work to `sk-git` and MCP orchestration to `mcp-code-mode` after the advisor has made the recommendation.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:57:This package is mandatory context for non-trivial Gate 2 routing. The live advisor scores prompts through `mk_skill_advisor`; this smart router controls which local documentation resources an agent should load while maintaining the advisor package.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:59:Routing model:
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:68:        +-- advisor_recommend on mk_skill_advisor MCP
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:72:        +-- ambiguous top scores -> surface top candidates and ask or route with caveat
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:83:- `feature_catalog/` documents current advisor capabilities and source-of-truth feature references.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:84:- `manual_testing_playbook/` documents deterministic operator scenarios for advisor tools, hooks, compatibility, daemon behavior and skill graph flows.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:91:| ALWAYS | Every advisor-maintenance invocation | `references/runtime/tool_ids_reference.md`, `references/runtime/standalone_mcp_shape.md` |
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:92:| CONDITIONAL | Intent signals match a resource domain | Matching canonical references, feature catalog slices, or playbook scenarios |
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:95:### Smart router pseudocode
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:97:This pseudocode captures the canonical documentation resource-loading contract. See [`references/scoring/advisor_scorer.md`](./references/scoring/advisor_scorer.md) for the actual runtime scorer mechanics.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:126:        "references/scoring/advisor_scorer.md",
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:148:        "references/hooks/skill_advisor_hook.md",
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:165:    "Confirm whether the task changes documentation only or executable advisor behavior",
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:191:                    raise ValueError(f"RESOURCE_MAP must target canonical references, not compatibility stubs: {intent} -> {guarded}")
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:218:    for intent, model in INTENT_SIGNALS.items():
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:219:        hits = sum(1 for keyword in model["keywords"] if keyword in text)
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:221:            scores[intent] = hits * model["weight"]
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:244:            "notice": f"No knowledge base found for advisor intent '{intent}'",
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:262:- **Advisor MCP unavailable:** fall back to Python `skill_advisor.py` shim, then to keyword matching against each skill's frontmatter `trigger_phrases`. Announce the degraded mode in the response.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:267:- Loading root compatibility stubs when canonical subfolder references exist.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:268:- Compatibility stubs without `deprecated_at` and `remove_after` frontmatter, or any router target that points at a stub before the removal-window grep passes.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:278:The package owns a dedicated MCP server named `mk_skill_advisor`. It registers **8 public tools plus 1 internal trusted-caller tool** (9 total). The tool ids stay stable:
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:282:- `advisor_recommend`
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:283:- `advisor_rebuild`
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:284:- `advisor_status`
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:285:- `advisor_validate`
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:295:The stable tool ids matter because live consumers already call them from hooks, Python compatibility shims, plugin bridges, doctor workflows, install guides and MCP clients. Server-level namespacing supplies the boundary, so callers use the standalone server without learning a new advisor vocabulary.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:297:The advisor implementation, skill-graph library and package-local database now live under this skill package, while memory remains focused on memory tools.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:306:- Keep the advisor database under `.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/database/`.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:307:- Keep public advisor and skill graph tool ids stable unless a later ADR explicitly changes them.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:309:- Keep `lib/skill-graph/` package-local to `system-skill-advisor`.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:314:- Let both memory and advisor MCP servers write the same advisor SQLite database.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:315:- Rename `advisor_*` or `skill_graph_*` public tools as part of documentation work.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:321:- The standalone advisor cannot build without a broader shared-runtime extraction.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:336:- `references/scoring/advisor_scorer.md` — lane attribution, fusion and confidence calibration.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:338:- `references/scoring/validation_baselines.md` — `advisor_validate` baselines and troubleshooting.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:349:- `references/hooks/skill_advisor_hook.md` — prompt-time hook behavior.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:362:- Skill discovery sees `system-skill-advisor` as a first-class critical system skill.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:364:- `advisor_*` and `skill_graph_*` public ids remain documented as stable.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:373:- `mk_skill_advisor` is registered as a standalone MCP server.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:376:- `lib/skill-graph/` database/query logic is fully migrated to `system-skill-advisor` (extraction complete).
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:381:- MCP clients that call `advisor_recommend`, `advisor_status`, `advisor_rebuild`, `advisor_validate`, `skill_graph_scan`, `skill_graph_query`, `skill_graph_status`, `skill_graph_validate` or `skill_graph_propagate_enhances`.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:382:- Doctor workflows that validate advisor health and rebuild state.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:394:- `mcp-code-mode` owns external MCP orchestration workflows.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:397:The advisor should recommend these skills. It should not absorb their implementation rules.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/runtime/daemon_lease_contract.md:3:description: "Workspace single-writer lease semantics for the freshness daemon: lifecycle, contention recovery, stale lease handling, failure modes."
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/runtime/daemon_lease_contract.md:6:  - "advisor lease semantics"
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/runtime/daemon_lease_contract.md:13:Workspace single-writer lease semantics for the freshness daemon: lifecycle, contention recovery, stale lease handling, failure modes.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/runtime/daemon_lease_contract.md:21:Defines workspace single-writer lease semantics for the advisor freshness daemon.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/runtime/daemon_lease_contract.md:27:- Checking why two advisor processes must not write concurrently.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/runtime/daemon_lease_contract.md:31:Only one advisor daemon may hold the workspace lease for a resolved database directory at a time.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/runtime/daemon_lease_contract.md:45:The `mk-skill-advisor-launcher.cjs` script enforces single-writer semantics at process startup before opening the SQLite skill-graph database. It calls `isLeaseHeld()` from `lib/daemon/lease.ts` to probe the lease state:
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/runtime/daemon_lease_contract.md:55:Daemon attempts lease acquisition on startup. The lease database lives next to the canonical skill graph database directory as `skill-graph-daemon-lease.sqlite`. Canonical means lexical `path.resolve()` followed by `fs.realpathSync.native()` when the path exists; if the directory did not exist yet, the daemon creates it and canonicalizes again before deriving the `workspace_key`.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/runtime/daemon_lease_contract.md:57:With the default configuration that directory is `.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/database/`. With `MK_SKILL_ADVISOR_DB_DIR` or `SYSTEM_SKILL_ADVISOR_DB_DIR`, the override relocates both `skill-graph.sqlite` and `skill-graph-daemon-lease.sqlite` together. On success the lease row records:
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/runtime/daemon_lease_contract.md:76:Every skill-graph database open sets `PRAGMA journal_mode=WAL` and `PRAGMA busy_timeout=5000` to improve concurrency safety and handle short-term lock contention. If the filesystem is read-only (EACCES), WAL mode falls back to `journal_mode=DELETE` with a logged warning.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/runtime/daemon_lease_contract.md:82:When two daemons start within the heartbeat window, both attempt acquisition. The lease database enforces a single row per canonical database-directory `workspace_key`, so only one owner can hold the lease for a given SQLite directory. The loser logs `lease-busy holder=<pid>` plus retries with exponential backoff: 1s, 2s, 4s, 8s, 16s, capped at 30s.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/runtime/daemon_lease_contract.md:84:If the lease holder responds with an MCP `advisor_status` call showing `live` trust state, the waiter accepts the holder as canonical plus exits without competing. If the holder is unresponsive past 3 retry cycles, the waiter inspects the heartbeat timestamp. If stale (>2x heartbeat interval), the waiter triggers stale-lease recovery (see §4).
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/runtime/daemon_lease_contract.md:108:During the Phase 006 compatibility window, launcher startup also probes the old lease database at `.opencode/skills/.advisor-state/skill-graph-daemon-lease.sqlite`. If that legacy database contains a live owner, the launcher exits `0` with `LEASE_HELD_BY:<pid> ... (legacy path)` and does not open the skill graph DB. If the legacy owner is stale or dead, startup logs the stale legacy observation and proceeds with the canonical lease beside the resolved DB directory. The launcher observes but does not migrate the legacy database.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/runtime/daemon_lease_contract.md:117:| Legacy rolling-start owner still alive | New launcher prints `LEASE_HELD_BY:<pid> ... (legacy path)` | Stop the old owner or wait for it to exit, then restart with the canonical lease path |
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/runtime/daemon_lease_contract.md:119:| Two daemons acquire concurrently due to filesystem race | SQLite database shows corruption (rare on macOS APFS, possible on NFS) | Stop both daemons. Delete `skill-graph.sqlite{,-wal,-shm}`. Run `advisor_rebuild --force` |
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/runtime/daemon_lease_contract.md:127:`MK_SKILL_ADVISOR_DB_DIR` and `SYSTEM_SKILL_ADVISOR_DB_DIR` override the skill graph database directory. The daemon lease database is co-located with that canonical directory, so two workspaces pointing at the same SQLite directory through different symlinks or path aliases share the same single-writer boundary.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/runtime/daemon_lease_contract.md:134:Recommended operator practice: keep strict single-writer mode enabled unless the intent is an isolated test run against separate DB directories.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/runtime/freshness_contract.md:3:description: "Formal contract for advisor freshness: trust states, transition rules, consumer obligations, daemon responsibilities plus failure modes."
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/runtime/freshness_contract.md:6:  - "advisor freshness"
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/runtime/freshness_contract.md:14:Formal contract for advisor freshness: trust states, transition rules, consumer obligations, daemon responsibilities plus failure modes.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/runtime/freshness_contract.md:22:Defines advisor freshness trust states, transitions, caller obligations, daemon duties and failure modes.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/runtime/freshness_contract.md:26:- Interpreting `live`, `stale`, `absent` or `unavailable` advisor states.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/runtime/freshness_contract.md:27:- Deciding whether to use, rebuild or fall back from an advisor result.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/runtime/freshness_contract.md:44:The advisor reports one of four trust states in every response that touches the skill graph:
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/runtime/freshness_contract.md:51:| `unavailable` | The advisor subsystem cannot be reached. Either the MCP server is down, the daemon failed or a hard error blocks all reads. |
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/runtime/freshness_contract.md:69:[source        | |  [advisor_rebuild succeeds]
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/runtime/freshness_contract.md:77:[db file       | |  [advisor_rebuild succeeds]
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/runtime/freshness_contract.md:90:- `stale → live`: `advisor_rebuild` completes successfully plus the generation counter advances.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/runtime/freshness_contract.md:92:- `absent → live`: `advisor_rebuild` runs from scratch plus succeeds.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/runtime/freshness_contract.md:94:- `unavailable → *`: subsystem recovers, fresh `advisor_status` call returns a real state.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/runtime/freshness_contract.md:100:Every caller that uses an advisor response must inspect `trustState` plus act accordingly:
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/runtime/freshness_contract.md:105:| MCP client (direct call) | Use recommendation directly | Call `advisor_rebuild` first if confidence matters | Call `advisor_rebuild`. Do not act on empty result | Wait for subsystem recovery or use Python shim |
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/runtime/freshness_contract.md:106:| Python shim (`skill_advisor.py`) | Use native response | Pass through with stale annotation | Compute fallback locally | Compute fallback locally |
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/runtime/freshness_contract.md:107:| Validation harness (`advisor_validate`) | Run as configured | Trigger rebuild before measurement | Trigger rebuild before measurement | Fail the validate run with clear error |
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/runtime/freshness_contract.md:113:- Treat `absent` as "no skill matches" and route to default. Always call `advisor_rebuild`.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/runtime/freshness_contract.md:126:- Announcing the new generation to subscribers via `advisor_status` response metadata.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/runtime/freshness_contract.md:127:- Holding a single-writer lease (`mcp_server/lib/daemon/lease.ts`) so concurrent advisor processes do not race on the SQLite file.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/runtime/freshness_contract.md:131:- Rebuilding the index automatically. Only `advisor_rebuild` mutates the SQLite database.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/runtime/freshness_contract.md:141:| Daemon dies | `advisor_status.daemon = "down"`, trustState may stay `live` until next file change but freshness detection lags | Restart the MCP server (`mk_skill_advisor` restarts the daemon on boot) |
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/runtime/freshness_contract.md:142:| Lease contention | `advisor_rebuild` fails with lease-busy error | Wait for current rebuild to finish, then retry. If stuck, kill the process holding the lease |
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/runtime/freshness_contract.md:143:| SQLite corruption | `advisor_status.trustState = "absent"` even after rebuild attempts | Delete `mcp_server/database/skill-graph.sqlite{,-wal,-shm}`, run `advisor_rebuild --force` |
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/runtime/freshness_contract.md:145:| Cache poisoning (stale entry survives generation bump) | Recommendations return outdated skill names | Run `advisor_rebuild --force` to invalidate caches |
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/runtime/freshness_contract.md:146:| Source-hash regression (rebuild succeeds but state stays stale) | trustState stays `stale` after `advisor_rebuild` | File a bug. The hash computation is broken |
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/runtime/freshness_contract.md:152:- [`tool_ids_reference.md`](./tool_ids_reference.md), `advisor_status` returns trustState, `advisor_rebuild` transitions stale → live.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/runtime/freshness_contract.md:153:- [`advisor_scorer.md`](../scoring/advisor_scorer.md), confidence calibration depends on trust state for some routes.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/config/db_path_policy.md:5:  - "system skill advisor db path"
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/config/db_path_policy.md:6:  - "skill-graph.sqlite advisor path"
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/config/db_path_policy.md:7:  - "advisor database policy"
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/config/db_path_policy.md:20:Defines the package-local SQLite database location for the standalone advisor runtime and documents the allowed test/CI override behavior.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/config/db_path_policy.md:30:The advisor owns its SQLite state inside `system-skill-advisor`; adjacent MCP packages must not become competing writers.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/config/db_path_policy.md:41:The advisor database lives inside the standalone advisor skill package:
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/config/db_path_policy.md:44:.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/database/skill-graph.sqlite
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/config/db_path_policy.md:64:ADR-001 constraint A requires DB-local ownership for the extracted advisor. The database is the advisor's runtime state, so it belongs with the skill that reads, writes, validates and rebuilds it.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/config/db_path_policy.md:69:- The advisor MCP server can be the single writer for `skill-graph.sqlite`.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/config/db_path_policy.md:70:- `system-spec-kit` keeps memory and spec packet state without owning advisor runtime data.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/config/db_path_policy.md:71:- Backups, cleanup and integrity checks can target the advisor package directly.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/config/db_path_policy.md:79:Production and operator docs should treat the package-local path as the default. A runtime override must not be used to silently re-collocate the advisor DB with `system-spec-kit/mcp_server/database/`.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/config/db_path_policy.md:85:Current package state keeps the database under `mcp_server/database/` and exposes it through the standalone `mk_skill_advisor` MCP server.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/config/db_path_policy.md:87:The `skill_graph_*` handlers and the lower-level `lib/skill-graph/` database/query library are advisor-owned and package-local.
.opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/feature_catalog/06--coverage-graph/02-coverage-graph-query.md:3:description: "Builds coverage-gap, contradiction, provenance-chain, unverified-claim, and hot-node read models."
.opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/feature_catalog/06--coverage-graph/02-coverage-graph-query.md:12:Builds coverage-gap, contradiction, provenance-chain, unverified-claim, and hot-node read models.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/feature_catalog/01--daemon-and-freshness/04-generation.md:21:`lib/freshness/generation.ts` writes the generation counter through a temp-file plus atomic rename. Post-commit publication makes the new snapshot visible to readers only after the counter has advanced. Corrupted counters are recovered when recoverable and reported as `unavailable` freshness when not. Generation bumps feed both `advisor_status.generation` and cache invalidation (see `lib/freshness/cache-invalidation.ts`).
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/feature_catalog/01--daemon-and-freshness/04-generation.md:29:| `.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/lib/freshness/generation.ts` | Library | Source reference |
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/feature_catalog/01--daemon-and-freshness/04-generation.md:30:| `.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/lib/generation.ts` | Library | Source reference |
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/feature_catalog/01--daemon-and-freshness/04-generation.md:31:| `.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/lib/freshness/cache-invalidation.ts` | Library | Source reference |
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/feature_catalog/01--daemon-and-freshness/04-generation.md:37:| `.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/tests/daemon-freshness-foundation.vitest.ts` | Automated test | generation bump atomicity |
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/graph/skill_graph_drift.md:25:- `advisor_status`, `skill_graph_status` or `skill_graph_validate` reports stale or inconsistent graph state.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/graph/skill_graph_drift.md:58:mcp__mk_skill_advisor__skill_graph_status({})
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/graph/skill_graph_drift.md:72:mcp__mk_skill_advisor__skill_graph_validate({})
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/graph/skill_graph_drift.md:98:mcp__mk_skill_advisor__advisor_rebuild({ "force": true })
