.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/graph/skill_graph_query_cookbook.md:131:    { "target": "cli-codex", "weight": 0.7, "context": "routes codex delegation requests" }
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/graph/skill_graph_query_cookbook.md:136:**Worked example**: The advisor enhances each CLI skill by routing prompts to the right one. Query returns the outbound enhancement edges, each carrying a context string explaining the relationship.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/graph/skill_graph_query_cookbook.md:159:    { "source": "system-skill-advisor", "weight": 0.7, "context": "routes implementation requests" }
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/graph/skill_graph_query_cookbook.md:164:**Worked example**: `sk-code` is enhanced by the advisor that routes implementation prompts to it. Query returns the inbound enhancement edges.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/graph/skill_graph_query_cookbook.md:166:**Gotcha**: The result reflects only declared inbound edges. Run `skill_graph_propagate_enhances` in `report` mode to find skills that should be enhancing this one but have not declared the edge yet.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/graph/skill_graph_query_cookbook.md:189:    { "skillId": "system-skill-advisor", "category": "system" }
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/graph/skill_graph_query_cookbook.md:220:**Worked example**: Most cli-* skills do not declare conflicts. They route per dispatch and do not interfere. An empty result is the common case.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/graph/skill_graph_query_cookbook.md:222:**Gotcha**: A non-empty `conflicts[]` signals a skill-level invariant. The advisor will refuse to surface both skills in the same recommendation set when conflicts are declared.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/graph/skill_graph_query_cookbook.md:233:{ "queryType": "transitive_path", "from": "system-skill-advisor", "to": "sk-code" }
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/graph/skill_graph_query_cookbook.md:241:  "from": "system-skill-advisor",
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/graph/skill_graph_query_cookbook.md:244:    { "skillId": "system-skill-advisor", "edge": "enhances", "weight": 0.7 },
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/graph/skill_graph_query_cookbook.md:250:**Worked example**: The advisor enhances sk-code directly. Path length is 1 hop. For deeper skills the path may include multiple edges of different types.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/graph/skill_graph_query_cookbook.md:275:    { "skillId": "system-skill-advisor", "inDegree": 9, "outDegree": 7, "total": 16 }
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/graph/skill_graph_query_cookbook.md:282:**Gotcha**: A high degree count does not mean a skill is high-quality. It just means many other skills point at it. Cross-reference with `advisor_validate` accuracy slices to see whether routing TO this skill is actually high-precision.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/graph/skill_graph_query_cookbook.md:305:**Worked example**: A healthy skill graph has zero orphans. Every skill should declare at least one outbound or inbound edge so the advisor can route to it via graph signals.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/graph/skill_graph_query_cookbook.md:307:**Gotcha**: An orphan skill will still surface in `advisor_recommend` if its explicit_author or lexical lanes score high enough. But the graph_causal lane contribution will be zero. Orphans are a signal to add at least one edge in the skill graph-metadata.json.
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/graph/skill_graph_query_cookbook.md:318:{ "queryType": "subgraph", "skillId": "system-skill-advisor", "radius": 2 }
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/graph/skill_graph_query_cookbook.md:326:  "skillId": "system-skill-advisor",
.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/graph/skill_graph_query_cookbook.md:330:      { "skillId": "system-skill-advisor", "depth": 0 },
