    21	---
    22	<!-- SPECKIT_TEMPLATE_SOURCE: spec-core | v2.2 -->
    23	<!-- SPECKIT_LEVEL: 3 -->
    24	
    25	# Phase 004 — Skill-benchmark mode (Lane C): design + build
    26	
    27	**Parent:** `122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode`
    28	**Type:** Implementation (new lane)
    29	**Status:** Planned (depends on Phase 001 + Phase 002 findings + Phase 003 rename)
    30	
    31	---
    32	
    33	## 1. Purpose
    34	
    35	Design and build **Lane C (skill-benchmark)** in the renamed `deep-improvement` skill: a benchmark that measures whether a *skill* is well-structured, well-routed, efficient, and useful **in practice** (how AIs actually discover/use it), and emits actionable, ranked remediation findings.
    36	
    37	The converged design from Phase 001 is authoritative, and the Phase 002 implementation playbook is the build guide; this spec is the working frame.
    38	
    39	## 2. Build (reusing the three pluggable seams)
    40	
    41	- **Fixtures (candidate-source).** Per-target-skill scenario set: realistic prompt + expected activation + expected reference/asset(s) + correct-outcome rubric, including negatives (should-not-activate). Authoring approach per Phase 001 RQ4.
    42	- **Dispatcher.** Hint-free harness (Phase 001 RQ2) that runs each scenario against an executor and captures the resource-load trace + tool trace (what was opened, order, call count). Model-agnostic, reusing the Lane B executor-routing map.
    43	- **Scorer.** Compare actual vs expected across the dimensions confirmed in Phase 001 (routing/activation accuracy, unprompted discovery precision/recall, efficiency/bottlenecks, usefulness ablation, structural connectivity). Reuse the Lane B deterministic-checks + pluggable-grader shape.
    44	- **Mode.** `scripts/shared/loop-host.cjs --mode=skill-benchmark`; records carry `mode: skill-benchmark`; report carries `scoringMethod`. Lane A/B remain byte-identical when the flag is absent.
    45	- **Command.** `/deep:start-skill-benchmark-loop` (`:auto`/`:confirm`). Reuse the model-benchmark command scaffold unless Phase 001 RQ6 says otherwise.
    46	- **Report.** Skill Benchmark Report: per-dimension scores + ranked bottlenecks + concrete remediations (Phase 001 RQ5). Diagnostic by default (no target-skill mutation); optional hand-off to Lane A.
    47	
    48	## 3. Resources to add
    49	
    50	- `references/skill-benchmark/*` (operator guide, evaluator/scoring contract, scenario-authoring guide).
    51	- `assets/skill-benchmark/*` (scenario-fixture schema, report template, default profile).
    52	- `scripts/skill-benchmark/*` (dispatch capture, scorer, report builder) + loop-host mode wiring.
    53	
    54	Per the fixed per-lane layout: Lane C adds exactly one subdir per area (`skill-benchmark/`) under `references/`/`assets/`/`scripts/`; genuinely cross-lane logic goes in `shared/`. The Phase 002 playbook fixes the shared-vs-Lane-C module split.
    55	
    56	## 4. Success criteria
    57	
    58	- Lane C runs end-to-end on ≥1 real target skill and emits a ranked, actionable Skill Benchmark Report.
    59	- Lane A/B behavior unchanged without the mode flag (regression check).
    60	- Repeatability evidence (variance across runs) is captured, mirroring Lane B stability.
    61	- `validate.sh --strict` green for this phase.
    62	
    63	## 5. Out of scope
    64	
    65	Remediating flagged skills (NG1). Replacing `sk-doc` validation or manual playbooks (NG2). `deep-loop-runtime` changes (NG3).

