.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/002-implementation-deep-research/research/gpt55/logs/iter-002.out:5074:.opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/README.md:33:Two skills, `deep-review` and `deep-research`, both run autonomous iteration loops. Both need atomic state-log writes. Both need single-writer locking. Both need a coverage graph that survives session crashes. Both need executor config parsing and Bayesian convergence scoring. Before this skill existed, all of that lived inside `system-spec-kit/mcp_server/` and got reached through four `mcp__mk_spec_memory__deep_loop_graph_*` MCP tools. Two consumer skills depended on the internals of a third, and every workflow YAML call paid the marshalling cost of MCP dispatch plus JSON parse.
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/002-implementation-deep-research/research/gpt55/logs/iter-002.out:5433:.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/changelog/v0.1.0.md:3:This first preview release establishes `system-skill-advisor` as a standalone MCP server that owns prompt-time skill recommendation. The package was extracted from `system-spec-kit`, given a dedicated MCP identity (`mk_skill_advisor`), decoupled from spec-kit's source tree and wired into every install + diagnostic surface. The release covers eight public tools (`advisor_recommend/rebuild/status/validate`, `skill_graph_scan/query/status/validate`) reachable through the `mcp__mk_skill_advisor__*` namespace. The 0.1 line keeps shadow-mode + parity gates in place while corpus and holdout metrics mature.
